etymologies: Middle English (in the senses ‘clean’ and ‘smart’): from French net ‘neat’; see neat. The sense ‘free from deductions’ is first recorded in late Middle English

crossReferenceMarkers: Often contrasted with gross (sense 2 of the adjective)
definitions: (of an amount, value, or price) remaining after a deduction, such as tax or a discount, has been made

examples.text: net earnings per share rose
the net worth of the business

definitions: (of a weight) excluding that of the packaging or container.
(of a score in golf) adjusted to take account of a player's handicap.
(of an effect or result) final or overall

examples.text: the net result is the same

definitions: acquire or obtain (a sum of money) as clear profit

examples.text: they sold their 20% stake, netting a huge profit in the process

definitions: return (profit or income) for (someone)

examples.text: the land netted its owner a turnover of $800,000

definitions: exclude a non-net amount, such as tax, when making a calculation, in order to reduce the amount left to a net sum

examples.text: the scrap or salvage value should be netted off against the original purchase price

etymologies: Old English net, nett, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch net and German Netz

definitions: a length of open-meshed material made of twine, cord, rope, or something similar, used typically for catching fish or other animals

examples.text: fishermen mending their nets

definitions: a piece of open-meshed material supported by a frame at the end of a handle, used typically for catching fish or other aquatic animals or insects.
shortDefinitions: net with handle for catching fish etc.

definitions: a structure consisting of a net supported on a frame, forming the goal in games such as soccer and hockey

examples.text: he turned Wilson's cross into the net

shortDefinitions: structure with net used as goal

definitions: a length of open-meshed material supported on a cord between two posts to divide the playing area in various games such as tennis, badminton, and volleyball.
a safety net

examples.text: he felt like a tightrope-walker without a net

definitions: a fine fabric with a very open weave

examples.text: net curtains

definitions: a means of catching someone; a trap

examples.text: the search was delayed, allowing the murderers to escape the net

definitions: a system or procedure for selecting or recruiting someone

examples.text: he spread his net far and wide in his search for success

shortDefinitions: means of selecting someone or something

definitions: the internet

examples.text: ensuring privacy on the net is an increasingly difficult job

definitions: a communications or broadcasting network

examples.text: the radio net was brought to life with a mayday

definitions: a network of interconnected computers

examples.text: a computer news net

definitions: catch or land (a fish or other animal) with a net

examples.text: damage caused when netting the fish
rabbits can be netted all the year round

definitions: fish with nets in (a river)

examples.text: he has netted the creeks and found them clogged with fish

definitions: acquire or obtain as if with a net

examples.text: customs officials have netted large caches of drugs

definitions: (in sports) hit or kick (a ball or puck) into the net; score (a goal)

examples.text: in six years Wright has netted 177 goals
Aldridge netted twice

definitions: cover with a net

examples.text: we fenced off a rabbit-proof area for vegetables and netted the top

etymologies: Middle English: variant of tun, both spellings being used for the container and the weight. The senses were differentiated in the late 17th century

definitions: a unit of weight equal to 2,000 pounds avoirdupois (907.19 kg).
shortDefinitions: unit of weight equal to 2,000 pounds avoirdupois

definitions: a unit of weight equal to 2,240 pounds avoirdupois (1016.05 kg).
shortDefinitions: unit of weight equal to 2,240 pounds avoirdupois

definitions: a unit of measurement of a ship's weight representing the weight of water it displaces, equal to 2,240 pounds or 35 cubic feet (0.99 cu m).
shortDefinitions: unit of measurement of ship's weight representing weight of water it displaces

definitions: a unit of weight or volume of sea cargo, equal to a metric ton (1,000 kg) or 40 cubic feet.
shortDefinitions: unit of weight or volume of sea cargo

definitions: a unit of gross internal capacity, equal to 100 cubic feet (2.83 cu. m).
an equivalent unit of net internal capacity.
shortDefinitions: equivalent unit of net internal capacity

definitions: a unit of refrigerating power able to freeze 2,000 pounds of water at 0°C in 24 hours.
shortDefinitions: unit of refrigerating power able to freeze 2,000 pounds of water at 0°C in 24 hours

definitions: a measure of capacity for various materials, especially 40 cubic feet of timber.
shortDefinitions: measure of capacity for various materials

definitions: a large number or amount

examples.text: all of a sudden I had tons of friends
that bag of yours weighs a ton

definitions: fashionable style or distinction

examples.text: riches and fame were no guarantee of a ticket—one had to have ton

definitions: fashionable society

examples.text: it is the most elegant establishment and half the ton was there
